{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:20:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11447"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11447"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.34,0.04,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110648"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4081"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92895"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"404"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4838"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110648"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old man is admitted to hospital with increasing agitation four days after repair of a neck of femur fracture. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, osteoporosis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. His regular medications include metformin, alendronate and tiotropium inhaler. He smokes 10 cigarettes per day and usually has one glass of red wine with dinner each night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears agitated and disoriented. Vital signs cannot be obtained due to his agitation. During the day, nursing staff noticed he was quieter than usual and appeared confused at times. Since the night staff started, he has been yelling and shouting at those walking past his bed. He continually attempts to get out of bed despite being repeatedly redirected by staff over the past hour. This has made him increasingly agitated to the point where he has now hit one of the nurses. He does not appear oriented to place or time. It is not possible to take a history or perform a physical examination due to his agitation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haloperidol intramuscularly","Lorazepam intramuscularly","Physical restraints","Urine culture","Donepezil orally"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute delirium with severe agitation. Delirium is an acute confusional state characterised by inattention, disorganised thinking, and altered level of consciousness that develops acutely and fluctuates throughout the day. Risk factors include advanced age, cognitive impairment, polypharmacy, and hospitalisation. Common precipitants include infections, metabolic disturbances, medications, and substance withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile medications are not needed for the majority of delirious patients, pharmacological intervention may be required when patients are significantly distressed, or could result in harm to themselves or healthcare staff, as in this case, where the patient has struck a staff member. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol intramuscularly\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate management. This antipsychotic medication can rapidly control severe agitation within five to 20 minutes, allowing for safe assessment and treatment of underlying causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELorazepam intramuscularly\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in most cases of delirium as benzodiazepines can worsen confusion and prolong delirium. The exception would be delirium related to alcohol or benzodiazepine withdrawal, which is less likely given this patient\u0027s minimal alcohol intake and the timing of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical restraints\u003C/strong\u003E should only be used as a last resort after all other management options have been exhausted. Physical restraints typically increase patient distress and disorientation, can cause physical harm, and have been associated with worse outcomes in delirious patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine culture\u003C/strong\u003E is reasonable to investigate for urinary tract infection as a reversible cause of delirium. However, the immediate priority is to ensure safety of both patient and staff through appropriate management of the severe agitation before proceeding with investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDonepezil orally\u003C/strong\u003E is an acetylcholinesterase inhibitor used in dementia management. It has no role in the acute management of delirium and would not address the immediate safety concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing stabilisation with antipsychotic medication, comprehensive assessment should include examination, blood tests, urinalysis, medication review, and consideration of alcohol withdrawal. Non-pharmacological strategies remain the cornerstone of delirium management, including reorientation, optimising sensory input, maintaining day-night cycles, and early mobilisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most patients with delirium can be managed without medications, but pharmacological intervention may be required when patients present a risk of harm to themselves or others.","Antipsychotics such as haloperidol are first-line medications for managing severe agitation in delirium.","Physical restraints should only be used as a last resort as they typically worsen confusion and agitation."],"references":["Caplan G. Managing delirium in older patients [Internet]. Aust Prescr. 2011 Feb [cited 2022 Jan 27];34:16-18. Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/australian-prescriber/articles/managing-delirium-in-older-patients#pharmacological-management","Psychotropic [published 2021 Mar]. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed 2 August 2025. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92895"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11447"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92895"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T18:09:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T18:10:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4081"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110648"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":